What is the DOM?

DOM (Document Object Model) is a representation of your HTML page that JavaScript can access and modify.

Example HTML:

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<body>

<h1 id="title">Welcome</h1>

</body>
</html>

JavaScript can access the <h1> element and change it.

Connecting JavaScript to HTML

Create two files:

index.html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>

<head>
    <title>DOM Practice</title>
</head>

<body>

<h1 id="title">Hello World</h1>

<script src="script.js"></script>

</body>
</html>
script.js
console.log("JavaScript Connected");

Open index.html in your browser and press F12 → Console.

Output:

JavaScript Connected
1. getElementById() ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐

Selects an element using its id.

HTML

<h1 id="title">Welcome</h1>

JavaScript

let heading = document.getElementById("title");

console.log(heading);

Output

<h1 id="title">Welcome</h1>
Change Text
let heading = document.getElementById("title");

heading.textContent = "Learning JavaScript";

Result

Learning JavaScript
2. querySelector() ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐

Returns the first matching element.

HTML

<h2 class="heading">JavaScript</h2>

JavaScript

let element = document.querySelector(".heading");

console.log(element);
Select by Tag
let heading = document.querySelector("h2");
Select by ID
let heading = document.querySelector("#title");
Select by Class
let heading = document.querySelector(".heading");
3. querySelectorAll() ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐

Selects all matching elements.

HTML

<p>Apple</p>
<p>Banana</p>
<p>Orange</p>

JavaScript

let items = document.querySelectorAll("p");

console.log(items);

Output

NodeList(3)
Loop Through Elements
let items = document.querySelectorAll("p");

items.forEach(item => {
    console.log(item.textContent);
});

Output

Apple
Banana
Orange
4. innerHTML ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐

Reads or changes HTML content.

HTML

<div id="box"></div>

JavaScript

let box = document.getElementById("box");

box.innerHTML = "<h2>Hello</h2>";

Result

Hello

Notice that the <h2> tag is rendered as HTML.

Another Example
box.innerHTML = `
    <h2>JavaScript</h2>
    <button>Click Me</button>
`;
5. textContent ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐

Changes only the text.

<h1 id="title">Hello</h1>
let title = document.getElementById("title");

title.textContent = "Welcome Priya";

Output

Welcome Priya
Difference: innerHTML vs textContent
innerHTML
title.innerHTML = "<b>Hello</b>";

Output

Hello   (displayed in bold)
textContent
title.textContent = "<b>Hello</b>";

Output

<b>Hello</b>

The tags are displayed as plain text.

6. style ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐

Change CSS using JavaScript.

HTML

<h1 id="title">Hello</h1>

JavaScript

let title = document.getElementById("title");

title.style.color = "blue";
title.style.fontSize = "40px";
title.style.backgroundColor = "yellow";

Result

Blue text
Font size 40px
Yellow background
7. classList ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐

Adds or removes CSS classes.

CSS

.red {
    color: red;
}

.big {
    font-size: 40px;
}

HTML

<h1 id="title">Hello</h1>
Add Class
let title = document.getElementById("title");

title.classList.add("red");
Remove Class
title.classList.remove("red");
Toggle Class
title.classList.toggle("red");

If the class exists, it removes it; otherwise, it adds it.

Check Class
console.log(title.classList.contains("red"));

Output

true

or

false
